\begin_layout Standard
The EPR argument requires an entangled state, over two particles, which
 was originally written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(x_{1},x_{2})=\int e^{-i(x_{1}-x_{2}+x_{0})p/\hbar}dp=\delta(x_{1}-x_{2}+x_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

In the modern notation, one can write this as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\psi\right\rangle  & = & \int\delta(x_{1}-x_{2}+x_{0})dx_{1}dx_{2}\left|x_{1}\right\rangle _{1}\left|x_{2}\right\rangle _{2}\\
 & = & \int\left|x\right\rangle _{1}\left|x+x_{0}\right\rangle _{2}dx.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Similarly, one can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\psi\right\rangle  & = & \int e^{-i(x_{1}-x_{2})p/\hbar}dpdx_{1}dx_{2}\left|x_{1}\right\rangle _{1}\left|x_{2}\right\rangle _{2}\\
 & = & \int e^{-ix_{1}p/\hbar}\left|x_{1}\right\rangle _{1}dx_{1}e^{ix_{2}p/\hbar}\left|x_{2}\right\rangle _{2}dx_{2}dp\\
 & = & \int\left|p\right\rangle _{1}\left|-p\right\rangle _{2}dp.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the first ket is that of the first particle, and second that of the
 second.
 An attempt to reproduce the precise argument, will not be made.
 Instead, we satisfy ourselves with the following simplified argument.
 We assume the principle of locality holds, which is to say that if two
 particles are sufficiently far away, then any change made to one particle,
 should not influence the other instantaneously.
 Given this assumption, consider two particles, which are sufficiently far
 away and that their state is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Now if the momentum of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is measured by observer 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, then observer 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, according to QM, will be able to predict the momentum of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if the position of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is measured, then observer 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 can predict the position of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 However, since the choice made by observer 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, can't influence particle 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (by the assumption of locality), it follows that particle 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 had both it's position and momentum well defined, without being measured.
 Since QM fails to yield the answer with precision, whereas as we have shown,
 the answer was precise, we are forced to conclude that QM is not a complete
 description of nature.
\end_layout

