\begin_layout Standard
Bohm gave a precise, but non-local description of quantum phenomena.
 Let us start with non-interacting particles.
 A particle is associated with (1) a position, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 & momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, precisely defined and (2) a wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Re^{iS/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 The postulates of the theory are: (a) Evolution of the wavefunction, is
 governed by Schrodinger's equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $i\hbar\partial\psi/\partial t=-(\hbar^{2}/2m)\nabla^{2}\psi+V\psi$
\end_inset

.
 (b) The particle is guided by the wavefunction: 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}=p/m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\nabla S=\hbar\text{Im}(\nabla\psi/\psi)$
\end_inset

.
 (c) The initial distribution of the particles is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=\left|\psi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The astute reader would've noticed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla S$
\end_inset

 is just the probability current, which entails that if the initial distribution
 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi(t_{0})\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, then it will do so at all times 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, thereafter.
 Before generalizing this to multiple particles, let us first see a quick
 consequence of this formulation.
 In the Orthodox Copenhagen interpretation, the double slit experiment is
 a source of mystery and the which slit question, that of confusion.
 In BM, since trajectories are well defined, one observes (TODO: add image)
 that the particle goes through precisely one slit and then later, forms
 the interference pattern.
 The wavefunction goes through both slits, and interferes to create the
 pattern.
 If one of the slits is blocked, then as expected, since the wavefunction
 can't interfere, the pattern is lost.
 We haven't spoken about measuring the particle yet, but if one notes that
 to measure the particle, the potential at one of the slits must be changed,
 then it is immediate that the interference pattern will be effected, since
 the wavefunction is affected by the potential at both slits, even if the
 particle passes through only one.
 One finds that by using the following multi-particle generalization, and
 an appropriate measuring scheme, one can show more precisely how the process
 of measuring effectively destroys the pattern, replacing the mystery with
 clarity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 interacting particles, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\nabla_{i}S(q_{1},q_{2},\dots,q_{N})$
\end_inset

 where note that the momentum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 particle, depends on the instantaneous positions of all the particles.
 Consequently, BM is an explicitly non-local, but complete description.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
