.
 A quick illustration is in order.
 Consider the following Stern-Gerlach setup; Quantum effects are considered
 only along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 A particle moves along the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis, with speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}$
\end_inset

, and it's initial wavefunction, given by a Gaussian centred at the origin,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=(1/\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma)e^{-x^{2}/2\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\int dx\psi(x)\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 It's spin state is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\chi\right\rangle =\left(\left|0\right\rangle +\left|1\right\rangle \right)/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
