\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{int}}=a\hat{p}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant that quantifies the strength of the field.
 Why this particular form works, will become clear momentarily.
 Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is large enough to neglect effects of free-evolution, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}(t)=e^{-ia\hat{p}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}t/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if the initial state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi\right\rangle =\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|\chi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\Psi(t)\right\rangle  & = & \hat{U}(t)\left|\Psi\right\rangle \\
 & = & \frac{e^{-ia\hat{p}_{x}t/\hbar}\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|0\right\rangle +e^{ia\hat{p}_{x}t/\hbar}\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|1\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{\left|\psi_{at}\right\rangle \otimes\left|0\right\rangle +\left|\psi_{-at}\right\rangle \otimes\left|1\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{x_{0}}\right\rangle \equiv\int dx\psi(x-x_{0})\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, viz.
 a Gaussian wavepacket centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 One can plot 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $z=v_{z}t$
\end_inset

, schematically as shown in the figure (TODO: put the figure), where regions
 enclosing, say 
\begin_inset Formula $70\%$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 have been outlined.
