 (given 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\ll at$
\end_inset

), obtaining the particle near 
\begin_inset Formula $x=at$
\end_inset

, is as probably as finding it near 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-at$
\end_inset

.
 QM doesn't make a deterministic prediction at this stage.
 According to BM, if in addition to the wavefunction, we assume that the
 particle was initially at some 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, then we can predict precisely where the particle will turn up.
 Infact, one can accomplish this with essentially no calculation.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}=\nabla S/m$
\end_inset

, a single valued function, it follows that trajectories of particles won't
 intersect, where recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Re^{iS/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, a particle that starts with 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

