\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\Psi(t)\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{-at}\right\rangle \otimes\left|0\right\rangle +\left|\psi_{at}\right\rangle \otimes\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Again, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 initially for a particle, it will follow the `up' trajectory.
 However, now this corresponds to spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, as opposed spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 We have thus demonstrated that we can't associate spin uniquely to a particle,
 and that it must only be associated with the wavefunction.
 
\end_layout

