\begin_layout Section
Determinism: The GHZ test
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One drawback of Bell's test, was that it's statistical nature.
 The GHZ test, takes this a step further and shows that one can't even conceive
 of having pre-defined values.
 The construction requires three observers with one particles each.
 Each observer can measure two properties, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, with outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 We start with the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\chi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|000\right\rangle -\left|111\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}:=\hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left|\chi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|\chi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where the property 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the projection of spin of the particle along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is that along the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis.
 Thus a measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 (the first observer measures 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and the other measure 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

), will yield 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 with certainty.
 Next, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}:=\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}:=\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}$
\end_inset

, which by symmetry, must also yield 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 for the said state.
 If these observables, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 had predefined values, then a measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\hat{B}\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 would be equivalent to measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}:=\hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

s appear twice for each particle, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since a measurement of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, it follows that a measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 therefore, must also yield 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}\left|\chi_{G}\right\rangle =-\left|\chi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which entails that a measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 must yield a 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we arrive at a contradiction and conclude that the assumption that
 the properties 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 had predefined values, must be incorrect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contextuality: The Peres Mermin test
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There've been various developments, of which the simplest, with effectively
 the same consequence, is discussed: the Peres Mermin test.
 In this test also, we will show that pre-defined values can't exist, but
 in addition, also define the notion of contextuality.
 Consider the following set of operators 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}_{ij}\doteq\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x} & \hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}} & \hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x}\\
\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}} & \hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y} & \hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}\\
\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x} & \hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y} & \hat{\sigma}_{z}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which have the peculiar property that all operators along a row (and along
 a column) commute.
 It is trivial to see that this holds for the first two rows and the first
 two columns.
 To see that this holds also for the last row and column, note the anti-commutat
ion relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{\sigma}_{x},\hat{\sigma}_{y}\}=0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}=i\sigma_{y}\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

, which one may check explicitly.
 Another interesting property is that the product of rows (columns) yield
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{i}=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{j}=\mathbb{I}\,(j\neq3)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{3}=-\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

, (
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\,i,j$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{i}\equiv\prod_{j}\hat{A}_{ij}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{j}\equiv\prod_{i}\hat{A}_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be verified easily by using the aforesaid relations and the fact
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, for every Pauli matrix.
 Using this property of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

, it is easy to show that no pre-defined values for operators can exist.
 Let us assume that pre-defined values do exist.
 Note that to get 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}=-1$
\end_inset

, we must have an odd number of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assignments in the third column.
 In the remaining columns, the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assignments must be even for each column.
 Thus, in the entire square, the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assignments must be odd.
 Let us use the same reasoning, but along the rows.
 Since each 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, we must have even number of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assignments along each row.
 Thus, in the entire square, the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assignments must be even.
 We have arrived at a contradiction and therefore we conclude that our assumptio
n that operators have predefined values, must be wrong.
 Note that unlike the GHZ test, the Peres Mermin test is state independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now in a position to discuss the notion of contextuality.
 We begin with defining a non-contextual assignment to be one, where the
 assignment depends only on the state (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 + hidden variables, if any) and the operator to which the assignment is
 being made.
 It follows that we had tacitly assumed a non-contextual assignment, that
 resulted in a contradiction.
 If we allow for the value of an operator, to depend on the context in which
 it is measured, where the context is meant to refer to a set of compatible
 observables, then the contradiction won't arise.
 For instance, if we imagine that all observables yield a 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, except 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{33}$
\end_inset

 which yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 if measured with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{32},\,\hat{A}_{31}$
\end_inset

 and yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 if measured with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{23},\,\hat{A}_{13}$
\end_inset

.
 If this doesn't appear entirely unsatisfactory, then you're on the right
 track and are encouraged to read the more detailed description given in
 Section [??].
